  ("71233E66-7ED1-46E4-9A53-07EBD65BAC05","https://www.nps.gov/isro/learn/management/your-dollars-at-work.htm","Your Dollars at Work","The collection of entrance fees and sale of passes at Isle Royale National Park directly impacts the sustaining and maintaining of visitor services."),
  ("9A254D54-058C-458D-BD57-869096B13033","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/beardiets.htm","The Surprising Diets of Brooks Range Brown Bears","Read the abstract and get the link to a paper on brown bear diets in the interior Arctic of the Brooks Range: Mangipane, L. S., D. J. R. Lafferty, K. Joly, M. S. Sorum, M. D. Cameron, J. L. Belant, G. V. Hilderbrand, and D. D. Gustine. 2020. Dietary plasticity and the importance of salmon to brown bear (Ursus arctos) body size and condition in a low Arctic ecosystem. Polar Biology."),
  ("47EAA7B6-D6E1-4939-A197-8F00768FB0D3","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/blackhistoryfova.htm","Black History at Fort Vancouver National Historic Site","Discover the stories of Black men and women from the history of Fort Vancouver and Vancouver Barracks."),
  ("F1D5C1F6-EE33-4848-B7B8-B7252E4FA7A1","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/horace-albright-s-national-park-service-legacy.htm","Horace Albright's National Park Service Legacy","Take a brief journey through the National Park Service career of Horace Albright."),
  ("8893B99F-9BFC-4A58-BB0F-FABD49AA94D1","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/responses-of-wildlife-to-low-levels-of-tourism.htm","Responses of Wildlife to Low Levels of Tourism","How does tourist visitation to the shorelines of Glacier Bay impact wildlife presence and activity? Is wildlife activity on popular beaches in Glacier Bay significantly different in a year with very little tourism (2020)?"),
  ("71DF5B3E-FDBF-418C-B21D-3B974349CA73","https://www.nps.gov/articles/vegmanpaal.htm","Vegetation Management at Palo Alto Battlefield","Palo Alto Battlefield is working to reverse some of the 20th Century activities. These activities have altered the physical environment and continue to harm the historic character of the battlefield. However, the park has the opportunity to restore or lessen altered landscapes on the core battlefield. Developing a comprehensive and integrated vegetation management plan would allow the park to fulfill its legislative mandate of preserving the historic character of site."),
  ("9DE2F012-AFB8-4D22-B28C-420A7FB7C227","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/ciro.htm","Visiting City of Rocks National Reserve","With its unique granite formations and stunning scenery, City of Rocks National Reserve in southern Idaho offers a multitude of opportunities for hiking, camping, climbing, and more."),
  ("30EA1AB7-CE07-45C6-AADC-BF2A40D2E490","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/miin.htm","Visiting Minidoka National Historic Site","Minidoka National Historic Site preserves the story of over 100,000 people of Japanese ancestry (Nikkei) in the United States who were forced from their homes and relocated to one of ten prison camps during the second World War. Today, visitors to Minidoka can view historic structures and new exhibits sharing this important piece of history."),
  ("4D6F3C53-AC50-40FE-B9EB-3CD11D08B5D1","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/of-night-skies-and-kerosene-lamps.htm","Of Night Skies & Kerosene Lamps","Growing up in a small city in Colorado, seeing the Milky Way galaxy was a nightly experience. As time went on, the city got larger, more lights appeared, the Milky Way was more difficult to see."),
  ("678CFD54-BE0D-463E-99BD-FBBBB6894743","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/sam-zuckerman.htm","Sam Zuckerman","Sam Zuckerman worked on the Sierra Nevada Network forest monitoring crew in 2017, and while he enjoyed the field work, this experience helped him decide he wanted to get involved with all the steps of carrying out a research project. He is pursuing a PhD in Natural Resources at the University of New Hampshire, where his research focuses on tree responses to drought in northeastern forests. Click on the article title to learn more."),
  ("5AB7CAA2-92CC-4E65-839F-6022E7665BA5","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/soidnewspaper2020_01.htm","Explore Your Southern Idaho National Parks","Discover southern Idaho's hidden treasures, including Craters of the Moon National Monument and Preserve, City of Rocks National Reserve, Minidoka National Historic Site, and Hagerman Fossil Beds National Monument."),
  ("4FFFE89B-E53E-47AE-B25A-934595E0FB32","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/texas-san-elizario-historic-district.htm","Texas: San Elizario Historic District","Wandering the laid-back streets of the San Elizario Historic District in Texas, one finds it hard to imagine the place as an action-packed crossroads of culture, commerce and military affairs. Yet in the 18th and 19th centuries, San Elizario’s adobe embrace held more than the charming air of history it exudes today."),
  ("84AC17CB-4F48-42A0-A674-28767ACFF28F","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/texas-socorro-mission.htm","Texas: Socorro Mission","Weathered wooden crosses and marble headstones punctuate the cemetery that fronts the graceful stepped facade of the 1843 Socorro Mission, just south of El Paso, Texas. Highlighting such surnames as Domínguez, Armendariz, Apodaca, Peña, López, Nuñez and Holguin, the cemetery documents over a century of life and death in the 17th-century settlement of Socorro del Sur, located on the southern segment of El Camino Real de Tierra Adentro, locally known as the Mission Trail."),
  ("FC91491F-AC8D-4EAB-8CD5-7699876A106B","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/texas-ysleta-mission.htm","Texas: Ysleta Mission","Learn about Ysleta Mission, one of the longest continually occupied religious buildings in the United States. It is the spiritual center of the only Indian Pueblo in Texas."),
  ("A772C480-87BE-4742-A299-A49D368F1DCD","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/completing-the-crater-lake-vegetation-map.htm","It's a Wrap: Completing the Crater Lake Vegetation Map","Dodging fires at Crater Lake National Park in the summer of 2017, the Klamath Network vegetation mapping crew gathered their last season of field data. The summer’s plots check the accuracy of the final map, setting the stage for its publication in June of 2018. Vegetation maps help us learn how park landscapes change over time, and help us identify unique or sensitive park habitats. The new map offers more detail and higher accuracy than any previously available to the park."),
  ("DEF46057-652D-4E7E-97E8-AD316836C444","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/pefo-upland-trend-brief.htm","Searching for Change in Petrified Forest National Park Grasslands","The Southern Colorado Plateau Network of the National Park Service has been monitoring grasslands in Petrified Forest National Park since 2007. Data collected from the park between 2007 and 2018 was analyzed to investigate how the condition of the grasslands changed over time."),
  ("EEA4A98D-6E9F-4CBB-9EB1-1C0006226668","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/webbers_falls_beautiful_fall.htm","Webbers Falls - 'really a beautiful fall'","Geography impacted Indian Removal and arrival into Indian Territory. Cherokee traveling on the water route went by steamboat which usually pushed or pulled a flat boat. Waterways in the 1830s were not maintained as they are today. Learn why Webbers Falls was a landing point."),
  ("370F94AD-63A1-4925-B24E-2A2992C7E4AA","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/webbers_falls_last_detachment.htm","Webbers Falls - Last Stop for the Last Detachment","Webbers Falls, Oklahoma, was the landing place for the final detachment of Cherokee into Indian Territory in 1839. The town was already settled by Cherokee who had moved much earlier than the Cherokee forcefully removed in 1838-1839 on the Trail of Tears. The site demonstrates how geography impacted Indian Removal and how the Cherokee rebuilt their nation in a new land."),
  ("10E035E1-18B6-4C42-B15B-B96FCB320D08","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/webbers_falls_old_settlers.htm","Webbers Falls - Old Settlers, New Homeland","Cherokee moved west of the Mississippi River decades before what is now known as the Trail of Tears. Early Cherokee settlers recognized the reality of white demand for land in the southeastern United States and moved west to Arkansas, only to relocate again following a coerced treaty in 1828. By the time of Cherokee removal, Indian Territory (today’s eastern Oklahoma) was a complex quilt of land patents for diverse American Indian groups removed from their homelands."),
  ("4BCC5287-1B09-479A-85B7-9DFBEE16E6CC","https://www.nps.gov/articles/early-explorers-before-george-catlin.htm","Early Explorers Before George Catlin","European fur traders and explorers documented and visited the quarries over 100 years before George Catlin made them famous. Learn more about their accounts, adventures, and exploits."),
  ("9EB7B9E9-D0B3-4430-B8C4-5544DD302FD1","https://www.nps.gov/articles/finnerty_winters.htm","Dual Career Couple Focuses on Helping Parks with Facility and Visitor Use Management","Working together for a Career and Life balance is something they manage daily."),
  ("6A03E282-35C3-4D19-9756-9120B7D9CB52","https://www.nps.gov/articles/ron_treants.htm","Ron Treants Steps Into Retirement","Farewell and thank you to the Denver Service Center Design and Construction Division for providing me an unbelievable and satisfying 32+ year career that exceeded my expectations. I was privileged to have worked on so many worthwhile, diverse, and notable design and construction projects during my tenure at National Park Service. I was especially humbled when asked to work, in some capacity or another, on National Historic Landmarks and a few of the most iconic structures."),
  ("8D18512B-811C-4278-92BC-8787F4A0DA2A","https://www.nps.gov/articles/the-men-of-nicollet-rock.htm","The Men of Nicollet Rock","In 1838, Joseph Nicollet's expedition to map the region between the Mississippi and Missouri rivers came through the pipestone quarries. The expedition camped for several days at the quarries and six men carved their initials (still visible today) into one of the rocks near Winnewissa Falls. This article provides brief snapshots into the fascinating lives of these men."),
  ("5F58043E-1BC1-4DFF-8A3B-10C1A9C75C44","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/independence-hall-world-heritage-site.htm","Independence Hall: World Heritage Site","For Americans, indeed for people around the world, there is no more potent symbol of individual freedom than Independence Hall. This World Heritage Site is located in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, where the dream of a free country of independent citizens became fact."),
  ("1F130CA3-0C55-489D-B37E-B67DC4DF82B3","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/monticello-and-the-university-of-virginia-world-heritage-site.htm","Monticello and the University of Virginia in Charlottesville: World Heritage Site","Thomas Jefferson (1743–1826) was the author of the American Declaration of Independence, third president of the United States, and a talented architect of neoclassical buildings. He designed his plantation home Monticello and his ideal 'academical village' -- the heart of the University of Virginia -- a few miles away."),
  ("9F846C9D-6700-4094-9C3A-8D7A72F8C880","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/san-antonio-missions-national-historical-park-world-heritage-site.htm","San Antonio Missions: World Heritage Site","The San Antonio Missions tell the stories of the people who came into the Spanish missions to live in the 1700s. Acculturating and converting the indigenous population in order to become Spanish citizens reverberates today in the southwest United States."),
  ("07E24D67-DE8F-413C-9949-1C15FD3E5BFA","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/san-juan-national-historic-site-world-heritage-site.htm","La Fortaleza and San Juan National Historic Site: World Heritage Site","The main elements of this World Heritage Site, found within San Juan National Historic Site, consist of La Fortaleza; the three forts of San Felipe del Morro, San Cristóbal, and San Juan de la Cruz (El Cañuelo); and a large portion of the City Wall, built between the 16th and 19th centuries to protect the city and the Bay of San Juan. They represent a fine display of European military architecture adapted to harbor sites on the American continent."),
  ("993946BC-9951-4D1E-AC27-509DAB88F891","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/the-20th-century-architecture-of-frank-lloyd-wright-world-heritage-site.htm","The 20th-Century Architecture of Frank Lloyd Wright: World Heritage Site","The World Heritage listing of “The 20th-Century Architecture of Frank Lloyd Wright” includes eight buildings in six states, designed and built over the first half of the 20th century by this preeminent architect. Each building has a different character and shows different solutions to the modern world’s needs for housing, worship, work, education and leisure."),
  ("F03254E5-6916-4C10-B16B-2C6A368D1748","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/monumental-earthworks-of-poverty-point-world-heritage-site.htm","Monumental Earthworks of Poverty Point: World Heritage Site","Monumental Earthworks of Poverty Point owes its name to a 19th-century plantation close to the site, which is in the Lower Mississippi Valley on a slightly elevated and narrow landform. Located on more than 400 acres, Monumental Earthworks of Poverty Point is a series of earthen mounds and ridges that overlook the Mississippi River flood plain in what is now northeastern Louisiana."),
  ("308BBCE1-0EEE-4625-A663-EF0EE13E7689","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/papahanaumokuakea-marine-national-monument-northwestern-hawaiian-islands.htm","Papahānaumokuākea: World Heritage Site","Papahānaumokuākea Marine National Monument is located in one of the Northern Pacific Ocean’s most isolated island archipelagos. Covering 139,797 square miles of tumultuous seas, craggy basaltic islets and low coral atolls, this World Heritage Site contains a world of superlatives."),
  ("41D56679-04C7-4DCD-B0EF-66498D188964","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/the-occupation-of-alcatraz.htm","The Occupation of Alcatraz","At first the Occupation was wildly popular, attracting thousands of Native Americans on a pilgrimage to the cold, windy island in San Francisco Bay."),
  ("FD1459C1-D348-41F2-85E3-0330F1813774","https://www.nps.gov/articles/how-the-world-heritage-convention-works.htm","How the World Heritage Convention Works","Learn about the Convention Concerning the Protection of the World Cultural and Natural Heritage, better known as the World Heritage Convention."),
  ("632E53CC-01EA-4267-BA78-FB3C72FED50C","https://www.nps.gov/articles/redwood-national-and-state-parks-northern-california.htm","Redwood National and State Parks: World Heritage Site","Redwood National and State Parks preserve some of California’s magnificent redwood trees -– the tallest and among the most impressive trees in the world."),
  ("4F2AD20D-8B1E-4531-9BC9-DD3979E09BBD","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/colonial-games.htm","Colonial Games","Learn about colonial games and make your own toy."),
  ("21199D14-ED4E-42B8-B242-AA80A849C7B1","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/grand-canyon-national-park-welcomes-new-branch-chief-of-fire-and-aviation.htm","Grand Canyon National Park Welcomes New Branch Chief of Fire and Aviation","Grand Canyon National Park Welcomes New Branch Chief of Fire and Aviation"),
  ("4284400F-6022-459B-9EE9-16887E5DDB07","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/poudre-wellness-program.htm","On the Trail to Health, Heritage, and Happiness ™ in Cache La Poudre River NHA","The Cache La Poudre River National Heritage Area’s new wellness program promises fun education and exercise for families, companies and solo adventurers alike. For a small fee, individuals and groups can sign up to enjoy themed wellness routes along the Cache La Poudre river, a nationally designated Wild and Scenic river. Participants can enjoy hiking, biking, scenic views of wildlife and the river, and can share their progress with the heritage area on social media."),
  ("4BAA0097-2138-45FE-B3DF-13210D18D859","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/preservation-and-protection-of-el-camino-real-de-tierra-adentro.htm","Preservation and Protection of El Camino Real de Tierra Adentro","The congressional designation in 2000 of El Camino Real de Tierra Adentro as a National Historic Trail put the spotlight on a pivotal three-century chapter of the ethnic, cultural and economic development of the American Southwest."),
  ("04DF107B-C610-4C46-8E5E-259138C587F7","https://www.nps.gov/articles/consultation-for-compliance-with-cultural-resource-laws.htm","Consultation for Compliance with Cultural Resource Laws","Cultural resource laws require consultation before finalizing Federal planning and implementation. Depending on the specific mandate, participants may be different. and include State and Tribal Historic Preservation Officers, Indian tribes, Native Hawaiian organizations, and other parties. This section of Cultural Resources and Fire is intended for any park personnel who may be involved in arranging and participating in consultations."),
  ("9565AD35-5E9C-41C3-85D9-28A2E362F083","https://www.nps.gov/articles/fire-management-and-cultural-resource-laws.htm","Fire Management and Cultural Resource Laws","This section of Cultural Resources and Fire reminds wildland and structural fire managers and park superintendents of the need to comply with relevant cultural resource Federal laws, DOI and NPS policies, and Executive Order 13175 when carrying out their responsibilities."),
  ("827A32EA-BFE7-458B-976C-DC03A8A0D83D","https://www.nps.gov/articles/structural-fires-and-cultural-resources.htm","Structural Fires and Cultural Resources","This section of the Cultural Resources and Fire module provides guidance for park structural fire coordinators (PSFCs); cultural resource managers; NHPA Section 106 coordinators; and park superintendents to ensure that cultural resources are fully considered and evaluated when developing and implementing structural fire management plans. Integration of cultural resources into the planning process will ensure that they are better protected during structural fires."),
  ("056983E6-BBD0-4396-B83C-14037D32E4B5","https://www.nps.gov/articles/vlsb.htm","Volcanic Legacy Scenic Byway","One of only 42 All American Roads in the Nation, the 500-mile route connects Lassen Volcanic and Crater Lake National Parks. The volcanic activity of the Cascade Mountain Range has created unique geological formations that can only be seen in this part of America."),
  ("3C340C77-7F86-4310-A807-A6E2E94BE99E","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/traditional-groups-along-el-camino-real-de-tierra-adentro.htm","Traditional Groups along El Camino Real de Tierra Adentro","In 1598, as Spanish colonizer Juan de Oñate led the first expedition to establish El Camino Real de Tierra Adentro north from Mexico into New Mexico, he made a surprising find: watermelon."),
  ("DB9EF160-3777-415E-BD13-4B2B98571118","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/2020-blue-pencil-gold-screen-awards.htm","2020 Blue Pencil & Gold Screen Awards","The National Association of Government Communicators (NAGC) Annual Blue Pencil and Gold Screen Media Awards highlight creative excellence and recognize superior government communications products and those who produce them."),
  ("C486D62F-2AF4-4C62-B97F-15BFD207DADF","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/at-home-or-school-for-young-children.htm","Coloring Fun for Young Kids","Color a few of the scenic places and special things found in Pictured Rocks. You can print these drawings that were created by our park rangers."),
  ("AF92EAAE-6285-4A30-8490-0DD8B9157516","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/global-perspectives-on-el-camino-real-de-tierra-adentro.htm","Global Perspectives on El Camino Real de Tierra Adentro","On July 30, 1857, residents of the southern New Mexico town of Las Cruces woke to an unusual sight. Assembled on the central plaza was an odd kind of cavalry, a U.S. military corps comprised not of horses or mules, but of camels and dromedaries."),
  ("6A2EE09D-FC6E-4E08-A68A-23F27D71991D","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/hfc-history.htm","HFC History","The idea for Harpers Ferry Center dates back to the early years of George Hartzog's tenure as director of the National Park Service. Hartzog became director in January 1964 and one month later named Bill Everhart chief of a new Division of Interpretation and Visitor Services."),
  ("9E3107B9-6BB7-4E84-9620-472A033C7048","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/my-idea-hfc.htm","My Idea HFC","Slowly this idea grew. Everhart was aided in pushing this concept with Director Hartzog by Vincent Gleason, then chief of the Division of Publications. Gleason, in fact, received a $500 cash award for suggesting that all media-related personnel be brought together into one office."),
  ("6CD411E2-AF48-4EF3-9614-01D862CDEEB7","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/separation-from-family-a-conversation-activity.htm","Separation from Family: A Conversation Activity","Due to recent circumstances, people today are experiencing separation from loved ones. Ulysses S. Grant was often separated from his family while serving in the army, prior to and during the Civil War. This separation caused him great anxiety and loneliness. Many families today can identify with Grant’s struggle and may also feel lonely or anxious during our uncertain times. Take a moment to complete this activity as a family."),
  ("07156237-C62F-4CB7-9BAA-EFE7BDAACBB7","https://www.nps.gov/articles/robertsimmonsprisonerconsciencealcatraz.htm","Robert Simmons","When Robert Simmons, an African American man from Savannah, Georgia, was brought to the foggy, windswept island of Alcatraz in the winter of 1918, he was thrown into the “hole,” a pitch-dark dungeon cell with slimy walls, crawling with rats. He was held there for 14 days. His crime? Simmons was a Conscientious Objector (CO) who opposed war and refused to fight on the battlefields of World War I."),
  ("F14EF384-24ED-4734-B177-18E21B470FF7","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/the-darkness-that-refreshes.htm","The Darkness That Refreshes","The Big Bend is dark. Probably darker than where you are from. It is so dark, that some people feel uncomfortable, as super dark nights are not what they are accustomed to."),
  ("C113FF40-7B17-406D-AD6A-F476BBED3FAF","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/the-trial-of-the-assassin-guiteau.htm","The Trial of the Assassin Guiteau","Charles Guiteau assassinated President Garfield in 1881. Read this article about his trial and convinction!"),
  ("9C6B3EE6-4214-4170-95B3-CA15CA55A088","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/ticks-in-acadia.htm","Ticks in Acadia","Through most seasons of the year, visitors taking part in most recreational activities throughout Acadia National Park need to be vigilant about avoiding the risks that ticks pose to them, and their pets. The park has partnered with researchers at the Maine Medical Research Institute, as well as graphic design students at the College of the Atlantic, to better understand and communicate about ticks as a serious public health concern."),
  ("6E134308-118E-42A3-9441-3EDBA8777E04","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/you-need-your-head-examined.htm","You Need Your Head Examined!","Phrenology, the examination of a person’s skull shape was a popular belief in President Garfield's lifetime. Learn more about the subject and what he thought of it."),
  ("03F7507D-D479-4BB5-9022-E06223E41942","https://www.nps.gov/articles/color-the-trail-birds-of-lewis-and-clark.htm","Color the Trail: Birds of Lewis and Clark","What birds were discovered during the Lewis and Clark Expedition? Learn about some of the ones these explorers saw for the very first time in a poster and coloring pages."),
  ("B89B2071-1FD6-46E5-94D1-23D9662D347B","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/2020-san-francisco-bay-area-city-nature-challenge-recap.htm","Community Science Update: 2020 San Francisco Bay Area City Nature Challenge Recap","2020 looked a little different for the City Nature Challenge, an annual community science event. The event encourages urban areas around the world to turn out the greatest number of naturalists, make the most nature observations, and find the most species. In previous years, people have traveled to parks to find nature and make observations. But given local shelter-in-place restrictions, organizers decided on a different strategy."),
  ("53B24973-2CAC-40D0-A9A9-9AA5C88B2F70","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/crmo.htm","Visiting Craters of the Moon National Monument & Preserve","Explore one of North America's most unique and scenic volcanic landscapes, where lava flows and cinder cones meet a vast sagebrush desert. Craters of the Moon National Monument and Preserve offers excellent opportunities for hiking, camping, and stunning night skies."),
  ("79CB6FFE-2D9D-4ABB-99CA-9363C9DF9A31","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/getaway-buis.htm","National Park Getaway: Buck Island Reef National Monument","When you think of visiting “America’s Paradise,” what comes to mind? Sparkling clear waters? Coral reefs? Palm trees swaying the breeze? History? All of these and more can be found in Buck Island Reef National Monument in the US Virgin Islands."),
  ("2BA8748F-1E1A-4916-AA7E-6AA4BE7AEF2E","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/honoring-marty-griffins-100-years.htm","Honoring Marty Griffin’s 100 Years: A Lifetime Of Environmental Achievements","L. Martin (Marty) Griffin, M.D. (born July 23, 1920) is a pioneering environmentalist and conservationist in California. Marty has been a leader in protecting and preserving unique ecosystems and the creatures that inhabit them."),
  ("AE20A859-2C71-4EFE-86DB-04BA44D71CC1","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/hoonau-kalaimoku.htm","Ho‘onā‘ū - Prolonging an Ancestral Breath: Kālaimoku","The fourth article in the Hoʻonāʻū - Prolonging an Ancestral Breath series by Kahakaʻio Ravenscraft is titled 'Kālaimoku' and it speaks to the depth of symbolism in Oceanic traditions. Featuring excerpts from a prayer uttered by the kālai ki‘i over the hafting of a stone-adze."),
  ("8BE4F159-C0CF-48D1-A189-487EC0DD942F","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/hudson-river-train-app.htm","All Aboard the Hudson River Valley NHA Train!","Take a train ride up and down the scenic Hudson River Valley while learning about such famous sites as the Schuyler mansion and Sing Sing prison. View the scenic river, wetlands, nature preserves. Hudson River Valley National Heritage Area’s new app allows history and nature enthusiasts from anywhere to take a free, virtual tour along the Hudson River."),
  ("24D4A24D-BF2F-4696-BC50-DF5239F0B834","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/new-article-offers-a-fresh-look-at-human-caused-climate-change-in-our-national-parks.htm","New Article Offers a Fresh Look at Human-caused Climate Change in Our National Parks","In 2018, Principal National Park Service Climate Change Scientist Dr. Patrick Gonzalez and others published the first spatial analysis of past and projected climate change across all US national parks. Now, Dr. Gonzalez has published an updated climate change assessment for the national parks. It synthesizes the results of the spatial analysis, but it also goes further."),
  ("039EECEC-4516-4487-9954-7AF8269726D9","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/peregrine-falcons-having-another-record-year-at-pinnacles.htm","Peregrine Falcons Having Another Record Year at Pinnacles National Park","The breeding raptor season is in full swing at Pinnacles National Park. Right now, prairie and peregrine falcon pairs are actively raising nestlings in cliff cavities throughout the park. This year, the raptor monitoring team has been able to continue most of its work in spite of COVID-19. And as raptor monitoring seasons go, it has already been an exciting one!"),
  ("4AE393F6-5595-4738-BD6B-154FD2FA9722","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/revolutionary-war-garfield-s.htm","Revolutionary War Garfields","Lexington and Concord was the first battle of the American Revolutionary War. Find out how an ancestor of President Garfield was involved in the battle."),
  ("018CD01F-A7CB-4563-A433-C86657F1E588","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/the-case-of-the-missing-harbor-seals.htm","The Case of the Missing Harbor Seals","Normally, biologists would head out weekly to survey harbor seals during their pupping season, from March through May. They would count adults and pups at eight pupping locations along the Marin County coast to be able to identify, and potentially help address, any unexpected changes in their numbers. In recent years, this monitoring might best be described as uneventful. Not this year!"),
  ("F803F37D-7C1D-48BD-B16C-0DF151107026","https://www.nps.gov/articles/1stkansas.htm","First to Serve-1st Kansas Colored Infantry Regiment","The 1st Kansas Colored Infantry first saw combat at the Battle of Island Mound in Missouri on October 29, 1862. In this skirmish, roughly 225 black troops drove off 500 Confederate guerrillas. Richard Hinton –the 1st Kansas Colored Infantry adjutant –had this to say on the 1st Kansas Colored's victory at Island Mound, he proclaimed, 'The men fought like tigers, each and every one of them, and the main difficulty was to hold them all well in hand.'"),
  ("18EF6039-DB4A-4DBD-8983-0543AA96BDC6","https://www.nps.gov/articles/alaska-s-matanuska-colony.htm","Alaska's Matanuska Colony","Alaska's Matanuska Colony. A book about a subarctic experimental farm colony established in 1933 as a New Deal resettlement community."),
  ("0CFCA60C-895C-42D0-B4E0-7A9641CF0953","https://www.nps.gov/articles/build-your-own-cannon.htm","Build Your Own Cannon","Experience a cannon firing, examine 3D models of artillery, and build your own paper cannon."),
  ("563233D2-0285-4864-ACBD-177CD7F40DD2","https://www.nps.gov/articles/freetolearn.htm","Free To Learn: African American Schools in Fort Scott","The passage of the 13th Amendment ended slavery in the United States but it did not immediately lead to opportunity and equality. Education was the key to helping students succeed. From the end of the Civil War until 1he 1950s, when schools were integrated, four African American schools did their best to provide opportunities for their students."),
  ("8DA8EAB2-2C3C-42F9-BD0F-DA0D5A1D0779","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/garfield-and-wilder.htm","Garfield and Wilder","Laura Ingalls Wilder was an author who wrote, Little House on the Prairie. Read how she and President Garfield are related!"),
  ("EBB55A4B-CAD0-40FB-B435-A2DEF51523B8","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/graduation-day-ulysses-s-grant-and-the-west-point-class-of-1843.htm","Graduation Day: Ulysses S. Grant and the West Point Class of 1843","Ulysses S. Grant graduated from the U.S. Military Academy at West Point in 1843. He later recalled that his education at West Point played a crucial role in his future endeavors, and that graduation day was one of the best days of his life."),
  ("B6666A2F-3661-456F-A367-32512C42E34A","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/making-rope-on-the-homestead.htm","Making Rope on the Homestead","Lois Butler demonstrates rope making as her father, Richard Brunkow taught her."),
  ("57C3CDC8-72CB-4A73-B1F1-7EEE576FA5AA","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/victorians-and-women-s-suffrage.htm","Victorians and Women's Suffrage","June is the 100th anniversary of the 19th Amendment. This article will look into the Victorian era and the women who fought for freedom."),
  ("F033171C-3C0F-4CD0-97A1-42CB4E9A2A54","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/on-the-move.htm","On The Move","The Lincoln family left Kentucky for Indiana in the winter of 1816. They would need to make sure they brought with them from their old home the things they need to survive. Figure out what items you think they would have needed to take with them and what they would leave behind!"),
  ("8052EF45-969F-42EF-AC0E-F9A20690024C","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/vladimir-kovalenko.htm","Vladimir Kovalenko","Vladimir (Vlad) Kovalenko worked on the Sierra Nevada Network forest monitoring crew in 2015 and 2016, and this work inspired him to go on to graduate school at the University of Montana in 2020. He is pursuing a Master's Degree in Systems Ecology, and his research will focus on Clark's Nutcracker ecology in the whitebark pine ecosystem in Glacier National Park. Click on the title of this article to learn more."),
  ("F23504EA-9376-4ACC-B707-92E42DF707D5","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/what-s-the-problem.htm","What's the Problem?","Do you enjoy math? Abraham Lincoln's total amount of education was about one year! He would often do math problems on his own at home. He even made his own workbook! Find the answer to these math problems to learn more about Abraham Lincoln and farm chores in the 1820s."),
  ("98B45CEB-7427-4021-BA1F-CBAFA4DCF9B3","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/20-ideas-to-recreate-responsibly.htm","20 Ideas to Recreate Responsibly","Spending time in nature is good for you, so we came up with 20 ideas of how you can #RecreateResponsibly. Try something new this summer!"),
  ("98A9453D-5142-4E97-80EC-3E5D946EAB4F","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/etc-aldrich.htm","E.T.C. Aldrich","Edmond Tilson Cantine Aldrich, ETC, was the neighbor of presidential candidate James A. Garfield in Mentor, Ohio. Read some of the diary entries he made during the summer of 1880 and the election campaign."),
  ("995113EC-2279-45E7-B3FC-8038F07EE713","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/june-nature-calendar.htm","June Nature Calendar","We have a ton of ideas for getting out and getting active in June. Have fun and remember to #RecreateResponsibly."),
  ("06BC536F-FFAE-4FDD-AF32-CAE7F3CFB307","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/-mantén-viva-la-llama-keep-the-flame-alive.htm","'Mantén Viva la Llama' - 'Keep the Flame Alive!'","Mantén Viva la Llama' --'Keep the Flame Alive!’ describes the theme of the Spanish Language Training Exchange (TREX) held near Santa Fe, New Mexico in October of 2019. The two week TREX program brings diverse fire practitioners from many Spanish speaking countries, including Argentina, Bolivia, Costa Rica, Ecuador, Guatemala, Honduras, Mexico, and Spain, together to build skills in prescribed fire, fire management, and fire ecology."),
  ("170A202A-B8AC-4E3B-B781-C97F6B9BD0D9","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/pictured-by-their-children-president-garfield-by-his-daughter-mary-garfield-stanley-brown.htm","PICTURED BY THEIR CHILDREN: President Garfield, by his Daughter Mary Garfield Stanley-Brown","Mollie (Mary) honored her father, President James A. Garfield, in an article written for the magazine, The Youth's Companion, in 1893. Read excerpts from the article here."),
  ("9763C5E8-566B-435E-A7A1-DDA873F21F74","https://www.nps.gov/articles/sarah-allen-profile.htm","Scientist Profile: Dr. Sarah Allen, Marine Ecologist and Science Program Lead","Dr. Sarah Allen's research on seabirds and marine mammals has brought her as far as Antarctica, but most of her career has been as a science advisor to the National Park Service. Read about her experiences studying penguins in Antarctica and her role in getting a nation-wide, long-term natural resource monitoring program off the ground!"),
  ("815E6495-E8B1-4A6E-8FD5-C689D1F8AB99","https://www.nps.gov/articles/sarah-venator-geologist.htm","Sarah Venator - Geologist","Sarah Venator is a geologist in the Alaska Region."),
  ("8467BCC9-E2D4-4431-992D-95D845EA458C","https://www.nps.gov/articles/sara-karpinski-park-guide-independence.htm","Sara Karpinski, Park Ranger, Independence National Historical Park","Sara Karpinski is a Park Ranger at Independence National Historical Park in Philadelphia. This park includes Independence Hall and the Liberty Bell. Watch the video to learn about her career in the National Park Service."),
  ("45486752-011F-4FC9-ABD3-CBDE567F4A8D","https://www.nps.gov/articles/staycurious_verant.htm","Stay Curious: Michelle Verant","Watch this short video about how Michelle, an NPS wildlife veterinarian, turned her childhood fascination with animals into a career where she helps protect the health of animals, humans, and the environment."),
  ("D66A702A-C3CF-4E22-9703-3573B64BC179","https://www.nps.gov/articles/susanmcpartland.htm","This Career Regularly Delivers New Discoveries","Susan sitting on a sand dune with her dog Smokey at Great Sand Dunes National Park"),
  ("4461321D-AF3D-4235-ACFF-0EE50918138E","https://www.nps.gov/articles/therese-picard-chief-ranger-for-law-enforcement-acadia-national-park.htm","Therese Picard, Chief Ranger for Law Enforcement, Acadia National Park","Therese Picard is the Chief Ranger for Law Enforcement at Acadia National Park in Maine. Watch the video to learn about her career in the National Park Service. Recorded during the 2020 centennial of the 19th Amendment, which guaranteed women's access to the ballot, one of the things Therese talks about is how the suffragists inspire her in her work."),
  ("98990B1A-6DD1-4064-93CF-1A3917C282B2","https://www.nps.gov/articles/vanpool.htm","Joining the National Park Service Archives Staff","After a few months with the National Park Service, archives technician Alexis Van Pool reflects on working as an archivist in the NPS."),
  ("06DFEE55-F3B7-450F-8C4B-69389DF4B8BB","https://www.nps.gov/articles/veteran-story-casey-mccabe.htm","Veteran Story: Casey McCabe","Casey McCabe served in Operation Iraqi Freedom and as a National Park Service employee has become a strong advocate for women veterans and trauma survivors."),
  ("43BD83C9-3584-410F-A5B1-83DEEBD86B1E","https://www.nps.gov/articles/veteran-story-ernestine-white.htm","Veteran Story: Ernestine White","Ernestine serves within the Directorate of Interpretation, Education, and Volunteers as the National Volunteer and Youth Program Coordinator located in Washington, DC. She works in collaboration with 14 regional and national program managers to oversee more than 300,000 volunteers who donated over 8 million hours of service in FY2016."),
  ("407CE936-3936-4229-AF82-DF4972A67C52","https://www.nps.gov/articles/veteran-story-jessica-zanetta.htm","Veteran Story: Jessica Zanetta","Zanetta served in airborne and air assault units in Operation Iraqi Freedom. She now works for Richmond National Battlefield Park."),
  ("E1BCCF9C-0E56-45DD-8A54-B96F1A4CB9FF","https://www.nps.gov/articles/veteran-story-lori-warner.htm","Veteran Story: Lori Warner","Lori Warner is a realty specialist in the Midwest Regional Office of the National Park Service. She is retired from the U.S. Air Force after 20 years of service."),
  ("7D37A458-B495-45A6-AF21-6A2218088A8A","https://www.nps.gov/articles/wildland-fire-susan-keys-receives-jeanie-harris-award-sagu.htm","Susan Keys Receives Jeanie Harris Award","Susan Keys, the fire program management assistant at Saguaro National Park, has been selected as the recipient of the 2013 Jeanie Harris Award. The Jeanie Harris Award commemorates the legacy of service of Jeanie Harris, an Intermountain Region fire budget analyst. The award is given to a National Park Service (NPS) fire program management assistant or a fire budget analyst, at either the regional or park level."),
  ("92E53290-B440-4445-BB9E-E15BF1E3A2D5","https://www.nps.gov/articles/women-in-fire-science-ellen-frondorf.htm","Women in Fire Science: Ellen Frondorf","Ellen Frondorf has worked in fire effects monitoring for the National Park Service. She shares her story of work in fire science."),
  ("FAF0B563-49DD-4168-84AE-C3E559DDD3B8","https://www.nps.gov/articles/women-in-science-fisheries.htm","Women in Science: Fisheries","Yellowstone National Park presents a unique opportunity for young professionals pursuing a career in fisheries management and research. Every year seasonal fisheries technicians, Student Conservation Association (SCA) interns, and volunteers from all over the world are hired to join the fisheries team. Many who start as technicians or interns here go on to pursue graduate education and careers in the fisheries profession..."),
  ("47FE830A-F522-44D2-AAFB-85D66BC93D8C","https://www.nps.gov/articles/yougogirl.htm","Dear Future Girl Conservationist","Every March we recognize Women's History Month. This year we celebrated with a video of some NPS women encouraging future female conservationists to keep going. Things might get tough, but we're here for you and we believe in you. You go girl!"),
  ("642E4259-E681-40D0-8B6F-59D9BBEFB00B","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/2020-worldfest-film-festival-winners.htm","2020 WORLDFEST FILM FESTIVAL WINNERS","In 2020 Harpers Ferry Center (HFC) won eight awards at WorldFest Houston. Many of these can be viewed over the summer through our upcoming film festival in celebration of HFC’s 50th Anniversary. (Note: The Special Jury REMI Award is given for a ranking of A+ and recognizes the top films in each category.)"),
  ("53627236-ACBC-4ED1-B303-9072647CAA37","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/schaus-swallowtail.htm","Partners Work to Bring Back Endangered Schaus Swallowtail","The Schaus swallowtail has been listed under the Endangered Species Act since April 28, 1976. Its risk of extinction is very high. That’s why a large group of partners in the Imperiled Butterfly Work Group work hard to increase the numbers of the Schaus swallowtail."),
  ("DC5FFDEE-6152-4368-98F1-BEAA98E9DF22","https://www.nps.gov/articles/2015-yount-winner.htm","2015 Harry Yount National Park Ranger Award","A visit to the Grand Canyon after college and Leslie Reynolds was hooked. Little did she know her love of national parks would take her on an incredible journey of public service and adventures in parks across the country. As the current chief ranger at Cape Cod National Seashore, Reynolds continues to inspire the new generation of park rangers and lead through example."),
  ("5CA6FEEF-86C6-43E7-BCA7-C74E6461C8A2","https://www.nps.gov/articles/acadia_playwright.htm","A Conversation with Andrea Lepcio, Playwright-in-Residence","In July 2019, Playwright-in-Residence Andrea Lepcio produced almost a dozen public performances of her site-based play, 'What Do We See? What Do We Do?' along the Compass Harbor Trail in Acadia National Park. The piece makes use of the life and home of park founder George Dorr to explore issues surrounding climate change. Video produced by Joseph Philipson and Nathaniel Boechat, Friends of Acadia, NPS."),
  ("0FA4D92D-D28B-4565-9DD5-41723D3D2A5F","https://www.nps.gov/articles/adrienne-lindholm-wilderness-program-coordinator.htm","Adrienne Lindholm - Wilderness Program Coordinator","Adrienne Lindholm is the Wilderness Program Coordinator in Alaska."),
  ("E42D2F1F-C2F1-460A-972E-E17414A411BB","https://www.nps.gov/articles/allaboutbats.htm","All About Bats","National Park Service wildlife veterinarian Michelle Verant shares expertise on bats and White Nose Syndrome, and engages with BioBlitz participants at the NPS Centennial celebration on the National Mall in Washington, D.C., May 2016."),
  ("6AFCD735-CC5B-4E44-8223-FD8F96662285","https://www.nps.gov/articles/amy_peabody.htm","Amy Peabody, Project Manager, National Park Service Design & Construction Division","I love the National Park Service mission of preserving our natural and cultural resources for this and future generations. Some of my most memorable personal experiences have been in our National Parks and I love that this job allows me to use my skills and expertise to support the mission while contributing to others having similar inspiring experiences."),
  ("6E78AD25-D7CF-49A6-B325-A4F1EB5F312F","https://www.nps.gov/articles/amy-larsen.htm","Amy Larsen - Aquatic Ecologist/Pilot","Amy Larsen is an aquatic ecologist and pilot for Gates of the Arctic National Park and Preserve and Yukon-Charley Rivers National Preserve in Alaska."),
  ("A82EE879-D456-4F78-AA8B-427BD8D23247","https://www.nps.gov/articles/amy-miller.htm","Amy Miller - Ecologist","Amy Miller is a supervisory ecologist and program manager for the Southwest Alaska Inventory & Monitoring Network."),
  ("B4662DF9-280F-4B35-921F-28C0434F41B9","https://www.nps.gov/articles/aps-19-1-1-download.htm","Below the Surface: Fish and Our Changing Underwater World","Alaska has over three million lakes, 12,000 rivers, and an estimated 6,640 miles of ocean coastline. Below the surface swim some of the world’s most abundant, healthy, all-wild fish, including salmon, halibut, and eulachon. Fish sustained Alaska Natives for millennia and continue to represent food and economic security for many people. Alaska Park Science 19(1):2020. ALSO, DOWNLOAD A PDF OF THE FULL ISSUE HERE."),
  ("1D35A9D8-4C59-4546-AF59-A618505E7CE4","https://www.nps.gov/articles/bethany_barron.htm","Bethany Barron, Chief, Construction Program Management Division, WASO Park Planning, Facilities, and Lands","The National Park Service offers a unique experience that you won’t find anywhere else. You get to work on the Nation’s treasures with people who are passionate about protecting resources and enhancing visitor experiences."),
  ("BE1D165A-8546-4B6F-A753-7D65AC57C91F","https://www.nps.gov/articles/bonnie-halda-chief-of-preservation-assistance.htm","Bonnie Halda, Chief of Preservation Assistance Region 1","Bonnie Halda, Chief of Preservation Assistance for NPS Region 1 (formerly the Northeast Region) talks about her career in the NPS. (Video)"),
  ("7BE851B7-6894-4DA9-9805-1B49B4AE94B6","https://www.nps.gov/articles/breeches-blouses.htm","Breeches and Blouses","Originally given no standard uniform by the agency, women working for the National Park Service fought for over fifty years to gain the right to wear the same uniform as their male colleagues. Learn more about the unfortunate, non-functional and sometimes truly outrageous uniform variants women suffered through before being treated equally."),
  ("A2BD3F3C-F32A-4422-ABD2-97305AFC8726","https://www.nps.gov/articles/carrie-miller.htm","A Special Talent Helps Share Pivotal American Historic Stories","Carrie Miller special talent helps share pivotal American historic stories."),
  ("AF9000DA-61FE-4FF5-8024-77AA5AA63FF1","https://www.nps.gov/articles/chiara_palazzolo.htm","Chiara A. Palazzolo, Project Manager at Delaware Water Gap National Recreation Area","I really enjoy being part of creating changes that improve how society uses transportation to recreate. I also value living the National Park Service’s mission “preserving unimpaired the natural and cultural resources and values of the National Park System for the enjoyment, education, and inspiration of this and future generations.”"),
  ("2457C85A-B238-4A62-AB10-3563125D20C0","https://www.nps.gov/articles/crystal-harmon.htm","Crystal Harmon","Meet Crystal Harmon, Procurement Technician"),
  ("CDC4FA6F-0EE1-4A0A-AFAE-5FF71B0CC0E2","https://www.nps.gov/articles/deskdig_powers.htm","#Sciencedeskdigs: Necropsy Kit","Learn how wildlife veterinarian, Jenny Powers, uses her necropsy kit to solve wildlife disease mysteries in parks. (Adapted from a post from the Instagram series called #sciencedeskdigs)."),
  ("7554006C-F070-4BED-BA90-0114E5518EA4","https://www.nps.gov/articles/deskdigs_blett.htm","#Sciencedeskdigs: Lichen","Ecologist, Tamara Blett, tells us all about lichen and how when we take a closer a look at things we can gain a whole new perspective of our natural world. (Adapted from a post from the Instagram series called #sciencedeskdigs that highlights the stories and work of NRSS scientists)."),
  ("8C0011F9-EE45-4303-9D04-212B74F0C451","https://www.nps.gov/articles/deskdigs_borgman.htm","#Sciencedeskdigs: Wildlife Camera","Learn about how Ecologist, Erin Borgman, helps parks monitor the animals that live there by setting up wildlife cameras to capture their presence and behavior. (Adapted from a post from the Instagram series called #sciencedeskdigs that highlights the stories and work of NRSS scientists)."),
  ("B27F1281-CCD9-4344-B621-A43AAA741D26","https://www.nps.gov/articles/deskdigs_brandt.htm","#Sciencedeskdigs: Baleen","Nicole Brandt, a biological science technician, explains what a strange looking broom is doing on her desk. (Adapted from a post from the Instagram series called #sciencedeskdigs that highlights the stories and work of NRSS scientists)."),
  ("3841F197-BCCB-478A-A52B-751027D40D83","https://www.nps.gov/articles/deskdigs_buttke.htm","#Sciencedeskdigs: Ticks","Ticks may be small, but veterinarian epidemiologist, Danielle Buttke, explains how they tell a bigger story. (Adapted from a post from the Instagram series called #sciencedeskdigs that highlights the stories and work of NRSS scientists)."),
  ("688E7641-73B3-4B6B-9A9D-5AE863A36B0D","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/zion-national-park-welcomes-new-fire-management-officer.htm","Zion National Park Welcomes New Fire Management Officer","Zion National Park Welcomes New Fire Management Officer"),
  ("033B9D4A-E7F8-4FE1-B899-69A19B6673C6","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/buffalo-national-river-conducts-2019-wilderness-prescribed-fire.htm","Buffalo National River Conducts 2019 Wilderness Prescribed Fire","In February and March 2019, crews from Buffalo National River and surrounding area conducted a prescribed fire in the Lower Buffalo Wilderness area. The park treated approximately 12,000 acres of forest, glades and woodlands with a low intensity broadcast burn to restore fire-dependent glade habitats, promote the growth of fire dependent species, and help reduce hazardous fuels."),
  ("20A1E667-8B06-429A-864B-1AA990109436","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/new-mexico-fort-selden-historic-site.htm","New Mexico: Fort Selden Historic Site","Today, Fort Selden stands as a ghost of itself and their memories in the shadow of the soft-curving Robledo Mountains, whose name honors the fate of Pedro Robledo, a member of the 1598 Juan de Oñate expedition and the first European to die on El Camino Real in what is now the United States."),
  ("2E4A0299-CACA-4F8F-9E07-98F9884150FF","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/trail-of-twelve-stones.htm","Trail of Twelve Stones","The Trail of Twelve Stones is a unique way to review some of the major events in Abraham Lincoln's life. Beginning just east of the Cabin Site Memorial, twelve historic stones area arranged in chronological order at irregular intervals. This trail guide, and the small bronze tablets located near each stone, briefly explain the events in Lincoln's life associated with each of the memorial stones. Several shaded, stone-bench rest areas are provided for your convenience."),
  ("3C2F5396-1854-43E0-A0E3-A042A0236B42","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/wui-fuel-break-indiana-dunes.htm","New Wildland Urban Interface Fuel Break Protects Community in Indiana Dunes National Park","To reduce the threat of wildfire and ease prescribed fire preparations, the fire staff of the Great Lakes Fire Management Zone, based at Indiana Dunes National Park, constructed a permanent fuel break along the southwest property line of Dune Acres. This fuel break provides a prepared defensive break to protect the community from wildfire encroachment, while at the same time maintaining the northern edge of the 800-acre Cowles Dune Prescribed Fire Unit."),
  ("781631AF-2BC8-46C4-86C2-F832FB0F3D34","https://www.nps.gov/articles/aps-19-1-8.htm","Zooarcheology of a 3,500-year-old Fishery on the Katmai Coast","Zooarcheology—the study of animal remains from archeological sites—reveals more than just a list of food items, it tells us how our natural surroundings and our climate have changed over time, how past peoples sustained their resources or over-harvested them, how our technology has advanced to allow our survival, how we relate to animals and each other, and how some things have remained the same. Alaska Park Science 19(1):2020."),
  ("5F385D00-507D-4FB6-9849-DEA4A8B1AABB","https://www.nps.gov/articles/fire-and-archeology.htm","Exploring the Fire and Archeology Interface","The Midwest Archeological Center (MWAC) worked with Midwest Region Fire Program to design and carry out experiments to collect information about the effects of fire on various classes of archeological materials. The goals of this project were to assess the fire/archeology interface to provide managers of Midwestern parks with information that will aid in decision-making concerning the stewardship of archeological and natural resources."),
  ("F3E22644-2754-4C54-A400-EC966616A4D3","https://www.nps.gov/articles/sky-island-fire-ecology.htm","Sky Island Fire Ecology","A history of three major fire regimes which have shaped the current landscape and vegetation of Chiricahua National Monument, as well as other sky island sites in the southwest."),
  ("99458E0D-EF89-4A06-82E7-04084543D0A4","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/hoonau-kuauhau.htm","Ho‘onā‘ū - Prolonging an Ancestral Breath: Kū'auhau","The third article in the Hoʻonāʻū - Prolonging an Ancestral Breath series by Kahakaʻio Ravenscraft is titled 'Ku'auhau' and it speaks to the importance of genealogy in Oceanic traditions. The article features excerpts from Kumulipo, a cosmology preserved from ka wā kahiko."),
  ("196757B7-7303-460A-A8A7-AE659B314A10","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/primarily-me-7.htm","Primarily Me 7: What's Missing?","Week 7: What's missing from your records? Explore primary documents and create your own record through the Primarily Me challenge!"),
  ("B6C9D1C4-143A-4A35-97C3-3118E5AB02FC","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/primarily-me-8.htm","Primarily Me 8: Keep it Safe","Week 8: How can you protect the primary sources you just made? Explore primary documents and create your own record through the Primarily Me challenge!"),
  ("0594983F-1FAB-4A38-876A-3E4FC557C652","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/new-mexico-fort-craig.htm","New Mexico: Fort Craig","The gritty crunch of footsteps on gravel, a dull desert buzz and the gentle flap of an American flag inspire a visitor to imagine the ghostly Fort Craig as a fully occupied U.S. Army garrison on the middle Rio Grande route of El Camino Real de Tierra Adentro."),
  ("76736D77-9985-484A-AE69-87DD8D182EA8","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/new-mexico-yost-draw.htm","New Mexico: Yost Draw","Somewhere along the meandering 1 ½-mile interpretive path that follows parts of El Camino Real de Tierra Adentro to Yost Draw, a visitor may begin to wonder what he or she is doing in the middle of the Jornada del Muerto—the Journey of the Dead Man."),
  ("F2CAA6C6-58D6-4293-BEA5-C617982A5598","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/frwy-100-days-countdown.htm","100 Years, 100 Days, 100 Facts","100 Years, 100 Days, 100 Facts - join Freedom;s Way NHA for their 19th Amendment Commemoration Countdown. Tuesday, May 19th marked 100 days until the centennial of the 19th Amendment. To commemorate the arrival of the historic event, Freedom’s Way National Heritage Area is counting down each of the days until the 19th Amendment’s anniversary, August 26th, by sharing one fact about suffrage history."),
  ("E8915999-F1E9-43C3-AA30-01EF1733006A","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/new-mexico-el-cerro-de-tome.htm","New Mexico: El Cerro de Tomé","A lone hawk circles over El Cerro de Tomé (Tomé Hill) on a breezy, blue-sky morning. Its black basalt slopes rising 400 feet above the Rio Grande floodplain, 10 miles south of Isleta Pueblo, Tomé Hill marks a dramatic break in the flat landscape, drawing both the bird’s-eye view and the interest of visitors below."),
  ("3667274B-C527-498A-9561-0EA3F63FF891","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/new-mexico-fort-marcy-ruins.htm","New Mexico: Fort Marcy Ruins","On August 19, 1846, three months into the Mexican-American War, U.S. Army Lieutenants William H. Emory and Jeremy F. Gilmer scaled an 80-foot bluff to survey the scene above the newly occupied Mexican city of Santa Fe."),
  ("559895E8-38DA-4DA2-A3CB-1BF5C2C29260","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/new-mexico-kuaua-ruins-coronado-historic-site.htm","New Mexico: Kuaua Ruins (Coronado Historic Site)","The Rio Grande bosque (woodlands) and the Sandia Mountains lie just beyond Kuaua Ruins, a prehistoric Tiwa village that was one of the largest Pueblo Indian settlements in the region at the time of the 1540 expedition of Francisco Vásquez de Coronado. The Rio Grande bosque (woodlands) and the Sandia Mount"),
  ("8C68210D-FA3A-47A4-9E67-1B6F7A60C03A","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/new-mexico-la-bajada-mesa.htm","New Mexico: La Bajada Mesa","A frigid wind powers across the juniper-studded grassland plain of La Bajada Mesa, fiercely determined to make its final destination. The travelers who braved wind and other weather to climb and cross the formidable mesa between the 17th and 19th centuries were equally determined."),
  ("F27C4423-4FB8-4C0E-8750-EC8EF9F87A06","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/new-mexico-palace-of-the-governors.htm","New Mexico: Palace of the Governors","The physical legacy of El Camino Real de Tierra Adentro is imprinted across the New Mexico landscape in the form of trail tracks, wagon ruts and lengthy swales that appear and disappear in the dirt like wandering ghosts of time."),
  ("F4994CD9-A2A6-4613-AA93-4A7D3FA5BFD8","https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/the-frontline.htm","The Frontline","Over the course of the last few months we have watched our way of life change dramatically as COVID-19 has forced people to learn to live much more cautiously. And yet, with all that is happening, some things continue on as they always have."),
  ("B042A1B7-9ADF-46FE-A7BF-6D5396BD27BD","https://www.nps.gov/articles/american-chestnuts-in-rock-creek.htm","American Chestnuts in Rock Creek","In 1904, a deadly fungus began killing American chestnut trees, once one of the most dominant trees of the eastern U.S. Despite overwhelming odds, some American chestnut trees survive today in Rock Creek Park."),
  ("9876613F-B27E-48C1-B068-B19F329543B4","https://www.nps.gov/articles/blri-bark-ranger.htm","I'm a Bark Ranger!","I'm Bark Ranger Bandit! I love helping with search and rescues to find people who are lost. Let me tell you about myself and my human."),
  ("70138D95-8F49-4562-A697-C0EB5ADBD570","https://www.nps.gov/articles/eastern-hemlocks-in-capital-region.htm","Eastern Hemlocks in the National Capital Region","Many evergreen, Eastern hemlock trees, typically found growing alongside forest streams, have succumbed to two insect pests. In the National Capital Region, we looked for surviving trees, and what other tree species are poised to replace hemlocks."),
  ("66F74B02-4CB2-42FA-8AEA-409819CD8246","https://www.nps.gov/articles/forest-regeneration-2019.htm","Forest Regeneration 2019","In 2019 tree seedlings and small saplings are in short supply in National Capital Area parks. Without these trees of tomorrow, what will our forests look like?"),
  ("C728AF95-5751-408C-B1F4-96251C350F18","https://www.nps.gov/articles/virtual-campout.htm","Live Virtual Campout","Join park rangers from the National Park Service from Saturday, May 23 through Monday morning, May 25 for our 2020 Virtual Campout. A wide range of activities will be offered and special guests will showcase the natural and cultural world with programs to include storytelling, living history and camping related activities. We encourage you and your family to “camp out” at home and virtually connect to our national treasures this weekend. Warm the hot chocolate, cook s'mores o"),
